description:
Create a class named EmployeeParser in your org with four methods that handle all JSON types:

1. getEmployeeId - returns 'employeeId' as String
2. getSalary - returns 'salary' as Decimal
3. isActive - returns 'active' as Boolean
4. hasDepartment - returns true if 'department' is NOT null, false if it IS null

Example JSON: {"employeeId": "EMP-001", "salary": 75000.00, "active": true, "department": null}

Method signatures:
public String getEmployeeId(String jsonString)
public Decimal getSalary(String jsonString)
public Boolean isActive(String jsonString)
public Boolean hasDepartment(String jsonString)

solution:
public class EmployeeParser {
    public String getEmployeeId(String jsonString) {
        Map<String, Object> data = (Map<String, Object>) JSON.deserializeUntyped(jsonString);
        return (String) data.get('employeeId');
    }

    public Decimal getSalary(String jsonString) {
        Map<String, Object> data = (Map<String, Object>) JSON.deserializeUntyped(jsonString);
        return (Decimal) data.get('salary');
    }

    public Boolean isActive(String jsonString) {
        Map<String, Object> data = (Map<String, Object>) JSON.deserializeUntyped(jsonString);
        return (Boolean) data.get('active');
    }

    public Boolean hasDepartment(String jsonString) {
        Map<String, Object> data = (Map<String, Object>) JSON.deserializeUntyped(jsonString);
        return data.get('department') != null;
    }
}

tests:
